│ THOUGHT: The problem is on line 171 where `ConstStep->getZExtValue()` is    │
│ called. For negative step values in types wider than 64 bits (like i65),    │
│ `getZExtValue()` fails because it tries to zero-extend a value that has     │
│ more than 64 active bits. The code should check if the step value can       │
│ actually fit in 64 bits before calling `getZExtValue()`. Instead, we should │
│ use `getLimitedValue()` which can handle larger bit widths by returning     │
│ UINT64_MAX when the value doesn't fit, or better yet, compare the constant  │
│ value directly without extracting it as a uint64_t.                         │
│                                                                             │
